<hr WIDTH="100%">
<h1>
<a NAME="Forecast"></a><font color="#FF0000">FORECAST</font></h1>

Based on weather forecast by ESO's <a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/">Astroclimatology</a>
team, lead by Marc Sarazin (ESO's weather and observing condition studies
specialist), on whose <a href="http://www.eso.org/~msarazin/">page</a>
one can find lots of information.
<h2>
<b><font size=+3>PTW Forecasts at Paranal and La Silla</font></b></h2>
Forecast for <a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/forecast/meteo/verification/index.html">Pressure,
Temperature and Wind Speed</a> at Paranal and La Silla. Both numeric values
and evolution plots are given.
<h2>
<b><font size=+3>Precipitable Water Vapour and Cirrus Cloud Cover Forecasts</font></b></h2>
Launch the&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<b> <a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/forecast/meteo/ERASMUS/forecast.html">Java
forecast applet&nbsp;</a></b>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
(from <a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/forecast/meteo/">ESO
weather forecast</a>'s <a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/forecast/meteo/ERASMUS/eso_fore.html">Water
Vapor and Cirrus Page</a>).
<p>
<hr WIDTH="100%">
<h1><a NAME="database"></a><font color="#FF0000">PAST INFO</font></h1>

<ul>
<li><b>ESO Ambiant Conditions Database:</b> This <a
href="http://archive.eso.org/asm/ambient-server">graphic interface</a>
lets you query the weather database for La Silla and Paranal since Aug.1998

<li><b>LOSSAM:</b> Line of Sight Sky Absorption Monitor, i.e. "was the night photometric". Updated daily.
<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/lasilla/asm/lossam/">La Silla LOSSAM for last night</a>, 
<li><a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/paranal/asm/lossam/">Paranal LOSSAM for last night</a>, 
<li><a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/forecast/meteo/CIRA/images/repository/lossam/">LSO and PO LOSSAM Archive.</a>
</ul>
<li><b><a href="http://www.eso.org/gen-fac/pubs/astclim/lasilla/asm/scidar/">SCIDAR</a>:</b> Scintillometer experiment at La Silla.

</ul>

<p>
<hr WIDTH="100%">
<h1>
<a NAME="ephemerides"></a><font color="#FF0000">Ephemerides</font></h1>

<ul>
<li>
<a href="http://www.ls.eso.org/lasilla/Sun-Moon/Sun-Moon.html">Sun &amp;
Moon Tables</a> for la Silla and for <a href="http://www.eso.org/observing/proposals/skycalc.html">other
sites</a>.</li>

<li>
The <a href="http://imagiware.com/astro/almanac.cgi">Daily Almanac</a>
(by Brian Casey , using Skycalc by by John Thorstensen) gives all the info
for a given night.</li>

<li>
Sun and Moon altitude and azimuth <a href="http://riemann.usno.navy.mil/AA/data/docs/AltAz.html">tables</a>.</li>

<li>
Lots of info can also be found at the <a href="http://aa.usno.navy.mil/AA/data/">US
Naval Observatory</a></li>

<li>
Not a link, but you may want to check out the great XEphem program, that
can be called by running /home6/ohainaut/exec/xephem on kila; for more
info on XEphem, go to its <a href="http://iraf.noao.edu/~ecdowney/xephem.html">home
page</a></li>

<li>
For specific objects: <a href="http://imagiware.com/astro/observability.cgi">Object
Seasonal Observability</a>, and the <a href="http://imagiware.com/astro/airmass.cgi">Hourly
Airmass Table</a> (by Brian Casey, using Skycalc by by John Thorstensen)</li>

<li>
More tools and links at ESO's <a href="http://www.eso.org/observing/support.html">User
Support Services and Tools page</a></li>
</ul>

